Let us write the supply and demand function as functions in the price
$p$. The text says that at a price $p$ the supplier produces $p-2$
units. Thus, the supply function must be

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
p = S(q) = q + 2
\end{align*}

At a price $p$ the consumer demands $65/p - 10$ units. In terms of the
demand function this translates into

\begin{align*}
p = D(q) = \frac{65}{q+10}
\end{align*}

By definition, the \emph{market equilibrium} is the intersection point
of the graph of $S(q)$ and $D(q)$. Let us denote this point by
$(q_e,p_e)$. To compute that point, we set both functions equal and
compute a solution for $q$:

\begin{align*}
S(q) &= D(q) \\
q + 2 &= \frac{65}{q+10}
\end{align*} And rearranging we obtain the equation

\begin{align*}
(q+2)(q+10) &= 65 \\
q^2 + 12q - 45 &= 0
\end{align*}

This is a quadratic equation and can be solved with the help of the
$abc$-formula: the solutions to a quadratic equation of the form
$ax^2 + bx + c = 0$ are given by

\begin{align*}
x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}
\end{align*}

Note, that in our problem the variable $x$ is replaced by the variable
$q$ and we have $a = 1$, $b = 12$ and $x = -45$. Hence,

\begin{align*}
q = \frac{-12 \pm \sqrt{144 + 180}}{2} = -6 \pm 9
\end{align*}

The solution $-6 - 9$ is not feasible, because quantities are always
nonnegative. Hence, we arrive at the unique solution $q_e = -6 + 9 = 3$.
We can calculate the associated price by using $D(q)$ or $S(q)$. Since
$S(q)$ looks simpler than $D(q)$ we use $S(q)$ and get
$p = S(q_e) = S(3) = 3 + 2 = 5$. Note, that this price is in between the
range given in the problem. Let us summarize:

\textbf{The market equilibrium is attained at $(q_e,p_e) = (3,5)$}

The second part of the question asks us to compute the \emph{consumer
surplus}. By definition, the consumer surplus is given by the formula

\begin{align*}
\text{consumer surplus} = \int_0^{q_e} (D(q) - p_e)\, dq
\end{align*}

The following steps compute this integral:

\begin{align*}
\int_0^{q_e} (D(q) - p_e)\, dq &= \int_0^3 \left(\frac{65}{q+10} - 5\right) \, dq \\
&= 65\int_0^3 \frac{1}{q+10} \, dq - \int_0^3 5\, dq \\
&= 65\ln(q+10)\Bigr|_0^3 - 5q\Bigr|_0^3 \\
&= 65(\ln(13) - \ln(10)) - 15 \\
&= 65\ln(13/10) - 15 \\
&\approx 2.05
\end{align*}

\emph{The consumer surplus is approximately \textbackslash{}\$2.05}
